SIMPLE: overbear
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overbear
<hw>O`ver*bear"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
bear down or carry down, as by excess of weight, power, force, etc.; to
overcome; to suppress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The point of reputation, when the news first came of the battle
lost, did <qex>overbear</qex> the reason of war.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Overborne</qex> with weight the Cyprians fell.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are not so ready to <qex>overbear</qex> the adversary who
goes out of his own country to meet them.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd.
)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To domineer over; to overcome by
insolence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overbear</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overbear
<hw>O`ver*bear"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To bear fruit or offspring
to excess; to be too prolific.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overbearing</ent>⟦br⟧
